sim_txt_beneficial: The coaching session taught me how to approach the simulator but I'm not sure if that was characteristic of my future classrooms.
sim_txt_cmsk:
'- I made sure students knew that raising their hands was more conducive to a safe and healthy environment and made sure to call on students as soon as their hands raised.
- I focused in on any misbehavior by telling the student to stop it immediately

sim_txt_concerns: I don't feel as though this prepared me for my future classroom because it seems like it's more designed for younger students. I think the concept of the simulator, at least the coaching that I received, helped me THINK about what I might do in my own classroom if students were acting up but I'm not sure I  would implement them.

I would want to see an IEP for the student just to have a basic idea on how to interact with him better or what kind of learning environments he excels in (group, paired, individual, etc.).
sim_txt_improve_exp: More students in the simulator, a classroom of five seems a little under what I would expect in a real classroom.

sim_txt_supports:
'-"Zen Zone" for Ethan to remove himself if he needs to take a minute to eliminate his disruptive behavior. 
-Tell students to not engage with Ethan or Dev when they try and ask them personal questions during a time where the teacher or other peers are talking. 
-Talk to Ethan one-on-one and have a behavior contract with him in hopes that there would be ways he would be willing to be an active participant in class. 
-Contact parent for extra support and figure out why Ethan acts the way he does. 
-Spend more time with Ethan at recess, or lunch, etc. to get to know him better as a person. 
-Have a jar in the class where students can put notes in personally to me about concerns they have or problems they would like me to address with the class. 
-Have class meetings to ensure we are all on the same page about respecting each other and being a community

name: Brownfield,Benjamin Anthony
sim_txt_beneficial: I think it was beneficial just being in a situation were significant behavior management was needed (at my teaching internships, not much has been required for a variety of reasons).
sim_txt_cmsk: I think students were able to focus on the task at hand, and that I was able to get them back on task when they started doing something else.
sim_txt_concerns: Each time I do the simulator, I feel that the students and situations portrayed are more appropriate for an elementary or middle school setting.  I have only been student teaching in high schools, and I am only interested in teaching at the high school level.  As a result, some of the behavior issues (and the need to respond to them) seem not very relevant for what I typically see at my placements.
sim_txt_eth_behavior: Inappropriate, off-task, and disrespectful
sim_txt_eth_contribute: Many things might contribute to his behavior: problems at home, some sort of mental health disorder, having a bad day, etc.
sim_txt_improve_exp: A little more time getting "coaching" could've helped, since this was very beneficial and helped me improve significantly in the second try.
sim_txt_supports: I think a special education teacher (or some sort of instructional aid) could be really helpful here, since they would be able to help with behavior management and work with specific students.  I also think that information about any medical conditions that the students may have could also be helpful, since it could help me understand why some students act out and how best to handle them.

name: Brownfield,Benjamin Anthony
sim_txt_beneficial: It helped me to experience how to work with disruptive students, which I have not done before.
sim_txt_cmsk: The class provided one class expectation (to be quiet and respectful in class), and the rationale for it (so that everyone can hear and learn).  However, some of the students were very off-task and did not focus on what we were doing.
sim_txt_concerns: None
sim_txt_eth_behavior: In this situation, Ethan was very off-task and focused on things (his phone, talking to other students, etc.) other than what the class was working on.  He was also somewhat disrespectful, since he talked over me several times and would not stop talking to his neighbor when I asked him to stop.
sim_txt_eth_contribute: A real student may act this way in class because of various behavior or psychological problems.  Also, some students may simply not enjoy school as much and be used to "acting up" or being the "class clown."  I would want to know more about Ethan's background, and his prior behavior in classes from previous years.
sim_txt_fbsk: The students were on-task and seemed interested in answering my questions.  Their answers also naturally led to other points and questions, which helped me to explain things they were confused about.
sim_txt_improve_exp: A little more preparation in terms of the lessons would have been helpful and would have made the experience less nerve-wracking beforehand.
sim_txt_supports: I think I would need more information on the behavior issues certain students may have, and maybe more information from veteran teachers about how to manage disruptive classrooms.

sim_txt_eth_contribute: I would assume that Ethan just doesn't have a lot of self-control.  We would need to work with him on his self-regulation skills.
sim_txt_improve_exp: I'm starting to have mixed feelings about the simulator.  I think it is an effective enough idea for practicing instructional approaches for small group setting,  but the classroom management scenario feels much more forced.  It feels like there is one specific way to get Ethan to stop his behavior (give a timely and specific order), but of course you don't know this your first time around.  The coach then tells you exactly what to do, and the next go around, Ethan magically responds.  It seems the goal is not to manage but to find the management technique you need to "beat" the simulator.   If this is the management technique you want us to learn, why not just tell us that?  Why not just have the coach come to our class as a whole and give this instruction and modeling?  It also odd, that given the extreme and constant emphasis in Curry on classroom culture, norms, and preventative action, that we would suddenly be asked to do management devoid of all of this and instead manage after-the-fact.  I wish that after-the-fact management would be covered more in our courses.
sim_txt_supports:
'-Well, we need rules already established.
-Students also need a clear sense of the classroom boundaries: when they are allowed to be silly or chatty vs. when they need to be focused on academic work

sim_txt_concerns: I don't really have any, I think its a neat tool!
sim_txt_eth_behavior: Ethan's behavior was very distracted but predictable. He seemed to need to move around and make some noises in order to be attentive at all to what was going on, but he was incapable of adjusting that kinesthetic energy long enough to even hear what I was trying to say.
sim_txt_eth_contribute:
Based on this interaction in particular, I think his behavior might stem from a need to fidget or move around while he is learning. I would want to know in this context if he might have a diagnosis of ADD or ADHD, and if there were any particular ways that he was learning to redirect his difficulty concentrating.

Another factor contributing to his behavior was likely that it was hard for me to set norms from the beginning since Dev was talking from the beginning (though he paid attention later) and therefore it didn't give Ethan a framework for what my expectations were.
sim_txt_fbsk:
I was able to redirect answers and get students to go deeper into the material than their original surface answers.

Students who gave very basic surface level responses were directed toward particular passages in the text in particular that gave them a better idea of the answer I was looking for.
sim_txt_improve_exp: I wish that we were able to move around in the simulator or have individual students move when they need to take a break from class discussion for a moment and reset their attention.
sim_txt_supports: I think that removing cell phones from the classroom would be a start for setting up a more productive environment. I might also consider reseating the students at different tables instead of all around one table so that any distracting behavior would not necessarily dominate the classroom. I would also like to be able to move around the classroom so that I could use my body language to stand next tot anyone who was carrying on extraneous conversations or fidgeting so much it distracted peers.

name: Buppert,Sydney Moeckel
sim_txt_beneficial: It forced me to be concise and quick even though I wasn't able to do this well.
sim_txt_cmsk: We got nothing accomplished the first time around. The second time, I got a few responses from students with suggestions for guiding principles for our classroom. If this were a real classroom, I would have been able to write them on the board behind me as points of reference and to build off of. and honestly, to help me remember them, but in this awkward situation, my discomfort got in the way of that.
sim_txt_concerns: This is my third time in the simulator and I wish I could have a sense of humor about it but I find it incredibly frustrating and demoralizing. There has never been any coaching element, so if there was some way that this was a learning experience for me, that would make it feel a little more bearable. Instead, it feels humiliating. And I think the very real dynamic and physical aspects of teaching and of getting to walk over and get down on a students' level and look them in the eye or touch their shoulder or calmly place my hand over their hand are really invaluable. And having context for a lesson would be invaluable. I don't think it's realistic at all that we would create classroom norms and expectations in 5 minutes. And we'd have already had some time briefly getting to know students by home visits or meet-your-teacher open house or even just in the hallway and as they unpack their backpack so we could be hard at work creating connections and building relationships. Our Classroom Management class and The First 6 Weeks of School text coach us to root norms and expectations in the hopes and dreams of the students after our first week getting them used to the school, reviewing procedures, and having them begin to trust each other and me. In the 5 minute simulator, that all goes out the window.
sim_txt_eth_behavior: He had great ideas but a lot of energy and needed something with which to channel it like pencil and paper to draw his ideas or a fidget.
sim_txt_eth_contribute: I imagine he might need some fidgets or a way to physically engage while having to listen and attend like being able to draw or stand at a desk.
sim_txt_improve_exp: I would rather teach in a real classroom any day.
sim_txt_supports: Time to build relationships. Activities with which to ground the learning or the lesson. Visual supports. A whiteboard/chalkboard. A way for students to get up and be engaged and active in the lesson rather than sitting the whole time. A way for me to have an anchor chart or the materials with which to make one.

the classroom norms and expectations scenario flies in the face of everything we are taught about classroom management and building classroom community. It would be helpful if there were some explanation about why we are supposed to meet  students cold and a produce classroom norms and expectations in five  minutes. I was busy trying to manage those behaviors in order to be heard but I could have had a more productive conversation if I hadn't kept asking for rules in general but instead had used the context developing right then and there.
- I wish I had known what recourse was available in the classroom and in the school. It was hard not to know my options for how to keep Ethan in line though I wanted to concentrate on building a positive relationship with him while being fair to the rest of the class.
sim_txt_concerns: How am I supposed to get feedback to improve? Am I just supposed to be more motivated to figure it out in the weeks ahead in our classes? I think it would only make sense to put us through this in this context if someone were going to be there to tell us "hey you did this well" and "hey, here are some areas to work on... let's talk about this." It was my understanding that this is what this experience was supposed to be.

With all of his energy, he seems to be a great candidate to be a teacher's helper running errands in the morning around school (or in the library) to burn some energy (although I'd watch carefully to see if his behavior is such that he can do this independently.

Feedback right then and there.

Disruptive and inconsiderate, but at the same time he did not seem aware of the fact that his actions were not appropriate. I would like to have the opportunity to talk with him one on one in a calm environment.  Hopefully having a conversation that helps expose him to the needs of others, and how his actions impacted them, then we could bolster a working partnership that helps the entire class.
sim_txt_improve_exp: This was unrealistic in that no matter what I did, I couldn't convince Ethan to calm down.  I couldn't pull him to the side, I couldn't move next to him and whisper this is inappropriate, I couldn't use hand signals to encourage him to stop.  Even an unruly kid can be encouraged to behave if they know that you are not going to overly punish them for acting out.
sim_txt_supports:
Personal relationships.  By not being able to have a personal relationship that allows for me to support Ethan and his actions, I have a hard time improving the classroom climate.  
Legitimate classroom expectations.  As we are able to have a positive relationship, then we can put into place a set of expectations that are reasonable and supported by all of the students.  And without first having a relationship, then I can not help the student to improve in the class.
Discipline referrals are not the way to go in this case because Ethan was not combative, temperamental, or otherwise disruptive for the sake of being disruptive.  He just was not recognizing that his actions were disruptive.

sim_txt_eth_behavior: distracted

silent activities

descript: TC maintained consistent voice throughout the sim, facial expressions changed slightly when students misbehaved.
rationale: TC supported students in generating 1 expectation. TC attempted with mixed success to redirect off task student behavior. Dialogue is mostly focused on student misbehaviors. TC affect Is calm.
name: Kim,Yewon
sim_txt_beneficial: '- It was a low stakes environment that I could practice "on-the-fly" strategies for interacting with real students
sim_txt_cmsk:
'- I redirected conversations that were not related to the classroom norms that we were discussing
- I included the entire class in the discussion of classroom norms, and made sure to address students by name.
sim_txt_concerns: These students seemed to be in the age group of middle school or younger, and I am not interested in teaching this younger age group. Although I see the objective benefit of having a low-stakes environment to practice skills such as behavior management, I am concerned as it is uncertain how exactly this would aid in my practice as a real-life teacher. If this simulation were phrased in a way that tracked the progress I had in handling certain situations as a teacher, and I could go and look back on my progress, it would have been a much more relevant exercise for me.
sim_txt_eth_behavior:
'- Ethan was distracted and had trouble staying on task throughout the activity--it would have been helpful to know if he had a 504 plan or IEP if his distracted behaviors were the result of any pre-diagnosed conditions, so that I could have responded with more knowledge to his behaviors
- Ethan is immensely creative and I can tell that his mind was constantly buzzing with ideas, and I found it rather funny and exciting
sim_txt_eth_contribute:
'- Ethan may just not like being in school, or being confined inside of a classroom
- He may have a 504 plan or IEP that identifies staying focused as an issue for Ethan. If this were the case, I would have to know this information instead of having to guess if it were true
sim_txt_improve_exp: '- If I were given a refresher or background information about each student
sim_txt_supports:
'- The students may need supports such as break times 
- The students may need to be taught how to work together in the classroom and be modeled what appropriate behaviors and interactions look like

descript: TC does not raise voice at students (warm but firm), does not show any physical signs of irritation
rationale: TC is not able to support students in coming up with classroom norms (comes up with some herself). TC is largely unsuccessful with redirecting off-task behavior (1/6 redirections include specific cues). There are very few moments throughout the simulation when all students are engaged in the discussion about classroom norms. Many disruptions were extremely lengthy, which detracted from the quality of the discussion. Majority of simulation is TC trying to redirect off-task behavior or trying to keep the conversation afloat (ignores last behavior).

name: Heard,Zora Ruby
sim_txt_beneficial: It helped me realize how I can be distracted by a difficult student, and hopefully with more experience I'll learn to stay focused and keep the students engaged!
sim_txt_cmsk:
'-I couldn't get the students to focus long enough to facilitate discussion.
-I had trouble keeping Ethan quiet enough to allow the other students to answer the questions.
-The distractions were making it hard for me to focus on what I was actually asking the students!
sim_txt_concerns: I have a lot to learn where classroom management is concerned!
sim_txt_eth_behavior: Ethan is disruptive, he is having trouble engaging and he is distracting the other students.
sim_txt_eth_contribute:
'-He might have ADHD
-He might just be seeking attention

-Why does he have trouble concentrating? Is it something that has been diagnosed?
-What is his best learning environment?
sim_txt_fbsk:
'-I asked students to give their responses to the reading before going into my questions in order to gauge interest.
-We were able to talk about the use of suspense and how it impacts readers.
-We were able to touch on how suspense might be read differently than excitement.
sim_txt_improve_exp: A bit more prep.
sim_txt_supports:
'-Knowledge of class structure.
-Cues to re-focus when students are becoming distracted.

descript: TC remained unruffled throughout, TC stayed positive and didn‚Äôt change tone or level of voice with redirections.
rationale: TC facilitated a well paced discussion focused on classroom norms and their rationale. TC supported students in generating 3 norms with rationale. TC efficiently redirected all off task behavior, so distractions were extremely brief. Majority of dialogue advances the classroom discussion. TC affect is confident.
name: Heard,Zora Ruby
sim_txt_beneficial: The coaching was helpful.
sim_txt_cmsk:

-I prompted students to think about why certain expectations are important.
sim_txt_eth_behavior: Distracting (to other students and myself)

Need for attention
Trouble focusing/ staying on task

sim_txt_supports:

descript: Maintained a consistent level and tone of voice, used lots of hand motions which seemed a bit nervous
rationale: TC supported students in generating 1 norm. TC attempted with mixed (2) successes to redirect off task behavior. Disruptions were mostly lengthy and detracting from the conversation. Dialogue is mostly focused on student misbehaviors. TC affect was calm.

name: Heard,Zora Ruby
sim_txt_beneficial: It has made me more aware of how I respond when I'm flustered.
sim_txt_cmsk: Everyone was able to participate in the discussion, there were a few interruptions but we moved past them.

-Attention seeking
-Difficulty concentrating
sim_txt_eth_contribute: He may have an attention deficit disorder.
